  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "If I deposit 9 lakhs by cheque into my saving account and withdraws it the same day, will the transaction come under IT notice?",
  "response": "Whether a deposit and withdrawal of \u20b99 lakhs on the same day will attract notice from the Income Tax Department depends on several factors, including your overall financial activity, past transactions, and the source of funds. Here\u2019s a detailed explanation:\n\n### 1. **Tax Implications**:\n   - **Deposit of \u20b99 Lakhs**: If you deposit \u20b99 lakhs by cheque into your savings account, it is recorded as a financial transaction. Under the Income Tax Act, banks are required to report cash deposits exceeding \u20b910 lakhs in a financial year for a savings account. However, since this is a cheque deposit, it is not directly flagged as a cash deposit. \n   - **Withdrawal on the Same Day**: If you withdraw the same amount on the same day, it may still be recorded as suspicious activity, especially if the transaction appears unusual or is inconsistent with your typical banking behavior.\n\n### 2. **High-Value Transactions**:\n   - **Cheque Deposits**: Banks report high-value cheque deposits above \u20b910 lakhs in a financial year. While \u20b99 lakhs is below this threshold, frequent or multiple transactions close to this amount may still raise red flags.\n   - **Repetitive Transactions**: If you frequently deposit and withdraw large sums on the same day, the bank may question the legitimacy of these transactions and report them to the Income Tax Department.\n\n### 3. **Source of Funds**:\n   - If the \u20b99 lakhs comes from a legitimate source (e.g., salary, business income, loan, or sale of assets) and is supported by proper documentation, you have nothing to worry about. You should be prepared to explain the source of funds if questioned by tax authorities.\n   - If the source is unclear or involves unaccounted cash, it may attract scrutiny.\n\n### 4. **Bank\u2019s Reporting Mechanism**:\n   - Banks use algorithms to detect unusual or suspicious transactions. A large deposit followed by an immediate withdrawal may trigger an alert, even if it doesn\u2019t directly violate any tax-related reporting thresholds.\n   - If the bank suspects any money laundering or tax evasion, they may report the transaction to the Financial Intelligence Unit (FIU) under the Prevention of Money Laundering Act (PMLA).\n\n### 5. **Precautionary Steps**:\n   - Ensure you have proper documentation for the source of funds.\n   - Avoid frequent or repetitive high-value transactions if there is no legitimate reason.\n   - If the transaction is part of your normal business or personal activities, you can inform your bank in advance to avoid misunderstandings.\n\n### Conclusion:\nA single transaction of \u20b99 lakhs deposited and withdrawn on the same day may not automatically trigger an Income Tax notice, but it could raise questions if it appears unusual or inconsistent with your financial profile. To avoid scrutiny, ensure the transaction is backed by proper documentation and aligns with your regular financial activities. If you are unsure, consult a tax advisor for personalized guidance.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
